    "text": "## Header\n\n# Alex Rivera alex.rivera@example.com\n\n## Education\n\nBachelor of Science in Computer Science, University of Georgia (2025) — GPA 3.82 / 4.00.\n\n## Tailoring summary\n\nTailored for the MS in Artificial Intelligence at University of Georgia. Emphasis: natural language processing, multi-agent reinforcement learning, on-device inference. Secondary emphasis: alignment with Director of Graduate Studies (computer vision, machine learning).\n\n## Selected experience & projects\n\n- **Retrieval-augmented code search in the UGA NLP Lab.** As an undergraduate researcher in the UGA NLP Lab I led a retrieval-augmented code search project that asked a narrow question: does span-level supervision meaningfully improve retrieval on low-resource code repositories? I built the evaluation harness, designed an ablation... - Led retrieval-augmented code search project end to end as an undergraduate researcher at the UGA NLP Lab. - Designed an ablation over span granularity and built the evaluation harness. - Authored a span-level error analysis that became part of a workshop paper contribution.\n\n- **Multi-agent RL for pantry restocking.** I built a multi-agent reinforcement learning environment that modeled a shared household pantry as a coordination game between independent restocking agents. The interesting part was not the reward function; it was the failure mode. Two agents with almost identical policies... - Implemented a multi-agent RL environment in PettingZoo and PyTorch around a pantry-restocking coordination game. - Diagnosed a free-rider failure mode and ran an ablation comparing no-communication baselines against a cheap communication channel. - Reported that coordination collapsed without communication and throughput improved modestly with it.",
